# Database Standards (Supabase / Postgres)

## Never Call the DB Inside a Loop

Accumulate data first, then send a single query. This applies even when using `Promise.all` — if the number of items is dynamic, batch at the DB layer instead.

```ts
// ❌ BAD — N round trips
for (const id of memberIds) {
  await supabase.from('profiles').update({ active: false }).eq('id', id)
}

// ❌ ALSO BAD — parallel but still N round trips
await Promise.all(memberIds.map((id) =>
  supabase.from('profiles').update({ active: false }).eq('id', id)
))

// ✅ GOOD — single upsert
await supabase
  .from('profiles')
  .upsert(memberIds.map((id) => ({ id, active: false })))
```

## Use Joins Instead of Multiple Queries

Supabase PostgREST supports nested selects. Prefer them over fetching related data in a second query:

```ts
// ❌ BAD — 2 queries
const { data: household } = await supabase.from('households').select('*').eq('id', id).single()
const { data: members } = await supabase.from('profiles').select('*').eq('household_id', id)

// ✅ GOOD — 1 query with join
const { data } = await supabase
  .from('households')
  .select('id, name, profiles(id, email, display_name)')
  .eq('id', id)
  .single()
```

## Select Only the Columns You Need

Never use `select('*')` in production paths. List columns explicitly to reduce payload size and prevent accidental exposure of sensitive fields.

```ts
// ❌ BAD
.select('*')

// ✅ GOOD
.select('id, email, created_at')
```

## Batch Inserts and Upserts

Build arrays in memory, then insert once:

```ts
const rows = items.map((item) => ({
  household_id: householdId,
  name: item.name,
  amount: item.amount,
}))

const { error } = await supabase.from('expenses').insert(rows)
```

## Always Check Supabase Errors

Destructure `{ data, error }` and return early on error. Never assume the query succeeded.

```ts
const { data, error } = await supabase.from('profiles').select('id').eq('user_id', userId).single()
if (error) return NextResponse.json({ error: error.message }, { status: 400 })
```

## RLS on Every Table

- Enable Row Level Security on every table in the `public` schema.
- Write policies that reflect the actual access model — do not default every table to the same policy without thinking it through.
- Never use `user_metadata` / `raw_user_meta_data` in RLS policies — it is user-editable. Use `raw_app_meta_data` or a dedicated `profiles` table joined on `auth.uid()`.

## Supabase Client Usage

| Context | Client |
|---------|--------|
| Server components, route handlers, middleware | `createClient()` from `@/lib/supabase/server` |
| Client components (browser) | `createClient()` from `@/lib/supabase/client` |
| Never | `service_role` key in any frontend or public-facing code |
